'''Margaret Anne "Peggy" Staggers''' (born January 12, 1945) is a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[West Virginia House of Delegates]] and is currently serving as an [[Whip (politics)#United States|Assistant Majority Whip]]. Staggers is an [[emergency physician]], [[paramedic]], and an [[Professors in the United States#Adjunct professor|adjunct professor]] at [[Mountain State University]].<ref name = "West Virginia Legislature">{{Citation| last=United States Congress| first=| year=2011| month=| title=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress: Harley Orrin Staggers (1907-1981)| publisher=[[Biographical Directory of the United States Congress]] website | isbn=| url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=S000778| accessdate=2011-12-03}}</ref>

== Early life and education ==
Staggers was born on January 12, 1945 at [[Naval Air Station Patuxent River]] in [[St. Mary's County, Maryland|St. Mary's County]], [[Maryland]] and was the eldest child and daughter of [[Harley Orrin Staggers|Harley Orrin Staggers, Sr.]] (August 3, 1907 <U+2013> August 20, 1991) and his wife Mary Casey Staggers.<ref name = "West Virginia Legislature"/> At the time of her birth, Staggers' father was serving as a [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|lieutenant commander]] in the [[United States Naval Air Corps]] in both the [[European Theatre of World War II|European]] and [[Pacific War|Pacific theaters]] during [[World War II]].<ref name = "United States Congress">{{Citation| last=West Virginia Legislature| first=| year=2011| month=| title=House of Delegates Members: Margaret Anne Staggers (D - Fayette)| publisher=[[West Virginia Legislature]] website | isbn=| url=http://www.legis.state.wv.us/House/Members/delmemview1.cfm?input=Delegate%20Staggers| accessdate=2011-12-03}}</ref> In 1948, Staggers' father was elected a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[West Virginia's 2nd congressional district]] where he served until 1981.<ref name = "West Virginia Legislature"/>

Staggers earned her [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] in 1969 from the [[West Virginia University]] [[West Virginia University School of Medicine|School of Medicine]] after which she completed her [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] in [[emergency medicine]].<ref name = "West Virginia Legislature"/>

== Medical career ==
Staggers is an [[Emergency department|emergency room]] physician practicing at Beckley Appalachian Regional Hospital in [[Beckley, West Virginia|Beckley]], [[West Virginia]].<ref name = "Porterfield">{{Citation| last = Porterfield | first = Mannix | author-link =| title =Legislators optimistic about health plan | newspaper = [[The Register-Herald]] | publication-place = Beckley, WV| volume = | issue = | date = May 24, 2008| page = | url = http://www.register-herald.com/local/x519098526/Legislators-optimistic-about-health-plan}}</ref><ref name = "Porterfield2">{{Citation| last = Porterfield | first = Mannix | author-link =| title =Staggers injured while treating patient | newspaper = [[The Register-Herald]] | publication-place = Beckley, WV| volume = | issue = | date = July 16, 2011| page = | url = http://www.register-herald.com/local/x202396383/Staggers-injured-while-treating-patient/print}}</ref><ref name = "Porterfield3">{{Citation| last = Porterfield | first = Mannix | author-link =| title =Staggers looks back on first year in House of Delegates | newspaper = [[The Register-Herald]] | publication-place = Beckley, WV| volume = | issue = | date = March 14, 2007| page = | url = http://www.register-herald.com/local/x519077813/Staggers-looks-back-on-first-year-in-House-of-Delegates}}</ref> In addition to her emergency medicine practice, Staggers serves as the medical director of multiple [[emergency medical services]] and [[emergency operations center]]s in [[Fayette County, West Virginia|Fayette]], [[Wyoming County, West Virginia|Wyoming]], [[Raleigh County, West Virginia|Raleigh]], and [[Boone County, West Virginia|Boone]] counties in West Virginia.<ref name = "West Virginia Legislature"/><ref name = "Porterfield4">{{Citation| last = Porterfield | first = Mannix | author-link =| title =Staggers seeks tax break for firefighters | newspaper = [[The Register-Herald]] | publication-place = Beckley, WV| volume = | issue = | date = January 23, 2008| page = | url = http://www.register-herald.com/archive/x518752017/print}}</ref>

Staggers briefly considered retiring from emergency medicine at Beckley Appalachian Regional Hospital following a July 7, 2011 incident in which an elderly female patient attacked Staggers as she attempted to provide aid to the woman.<ref name = "Porterfield2"/> The elderly patient scratched Staggers' face, drawing blood.<ref name = "Porterfield2"/> Staggers returned to her legislative duties in [[Charleston, West Virginia|Charleston]] the week after the attack.<ref name = "Porterfield2"/>

== Politicial activities ==
In 1978, Staggers served as a delegate to the [[1976 Democratic National Convention]] at [[Madison Square Garden]] in [[New York City]] where she voted to nominate [[United States Senator]] [[Robert Byrd]] as the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[United States presidential election, 1976|candidate for the 1976 United States presidential election]].<ref name = "West Virginia Legislature"/>

===West Virginia House of Delegates tenure===
Staggers was elected to the [[West Virginia House of Delegates]] from the 29th district representing [[Fayette County, West Virginia|Fayette County]], [[West Virginia]] in 2006.<ref name = "West Virginia Legislature"/> She is currently serving as an [[Whip (politics)#United States|Assistant Majority Whip]], vice-chairperson on the Roads and Transportation Committee, and a member of the Government Organization Committee, Health and Human Resources Committee, Veterans Affairs/Homeland Security Committee, and the House Select Committee on Redistricting.<ref name = "West Virginia Legislature"/> During the 79th session of the [[West Virginia Legislature]], Staggers served as vice-chairperson of the Committee on Enrolled Bills.<ref name = "West Virginia Legislature"/>

In 2008, Staggers authored legislation extending a [[tax break]] to volunteer [[firefighter]]s excusing them from tax that are due beyond what is already withheld from paychecks.<ref name = "Porterfield4"/> Later in 2008, before the passage of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act of 2010]], Staggers worked on one of four special work groups in the West Virginia House of Delegates with the goal of developing a [[universal health care]] system in West Virginia in lieu of a national health care reform policy.<ref name = "Porterfield"/> Staggers' work group was tasked with simplifying the administrative end of a universal healthcare system in West Virginia with the other three study groups dedicated to technology, chronic conditions, and wellness and prevention.<ref name = "Porterfield"/> 

On the 30th anniversary of the passage of the [[Staggers Rail Act|Staggers Rail Act of 1980]] authored by her father, Congressman Harley Orrin Staggers, Sr., Staggers wrote an [[editorial]] in the ''[[Charleston Gazette-Mail]]'' praising the [[Bipartisanship|bipartisan]] effort in the [[United States Congress]] led by her father to [[Deregulation|deregulate]] the [[Rail transportation in the United States|United States railroad industry]].<ref name = "Staggers Op-Ed">{{Citation| last = Staggers| first = Margaret Anne | author-link =| title =Dr. Margaret Staggers: Staggers Act saved railroads| newspaper = [[Charleston Gazette-Mail]] | publication-place = Charleston, WV| volume = | issue = | date = October 4, 2010| page = | url = http://wvgazette.com/Opinion/OpEdCommentaries/201010040692}}</ref>

== Affiliations ==
Staggers is a former president of the West Virginia Chapter of the [[American College of Emergency Physicians]], past chairman and member of the West Virginia Chapter of the [[American Heart Association]], and a fellow of the American College of Emergency Physicians and [[American Academy of Family Physicians]].<ref name = "West Virginia Legislature"/>

